McNeill Hall   :  \n Usage: \n - The three-story building, which was designed and built to help UNCW address the chronic shortage of qualified nurses in North Carolina, brings the latest technology into educational approaches. \n \n McNeill Hall includes: \n - State-of-the-art classrooms; distance learning, tele-classroms, enhanced web-based teaching strategies \n - Patient simulation labs, known as the Technology Enhanced Applied Learning (TEAL) Center \n - Hospital-quality equipment \n - Faculty offices \n - Lecture hall \n - Spaces for research
Teaching Lab   :   \n Departments and Usage: \n - The Teaching Lab Building is the second building in the Health Science Quadrangle, which is a key element of the UNCW Campus Master Plan Update 2010. The first building to be constructed in the quadrangle was McNeill Hall. \n - The Teaching Lab Building is a three-story building with offices, general purpose classrooms and labs.   \n Primary user groups include: \n - Psychology \n - Environmental Studies
Wagoner Dining Hall   : \n  Current Usage: \n - Wagoner Hall is the primary food service area for students and faculty. This facility offers RFoC ("Real Food on Campus) - a variety of cutting-edge American entrees, ethnically-inspired foods, vegetarian selections and lots more, all prepared right before your eyes. \n - The entrance to Madeline Suite, a catered dining facility suitable for meetings and special events, is located on the northeast side of Wagoner Hall. \n - WAG OUT (Wagoner To Go) and catering offices are located on the southwest side of Wagoner Hall.
